================================================================================
REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emAnything.h: type-erased value container with refcounted sharing.

7 files outside emCore use this type (all in emStocks).

C++ provides two classes:
  emAnything            — holds a refcounted AbstractSharedData pointer.
                          Copies share data (refcount bump).
  emCastAnything<T>     — wraps a T into emAnything, or extracts T from
                          emAnything via dynamic_cast. Returns NULL on
                          type mismatch.

Rust equivalents (verified):
  emAnything             -> Option<Box<dyn Any>>
    emListBox.rs:234       — data: Option<Box<dyn Any>> (Item struct member)
    emListBox.rs:661       — GetItemData returns Option<&dyn Any>
    emListBox.rs:666       — SetItemData takes Option<Box<dyn Any>>
  emCastAnything<T>      -> Any::downcast_ref::<T>()
    emPanel.rs:37-45       — as_any()/as_any_mut() trait for downcasting

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  Refcounted sharing — C++ emAnything copies share data via refcount.
    Rust Box<dyn Any> is move-only. Rust GetItemData returns a borrow
    (Option<&dyn Any>) instead of a refcounted copy.

Open question investigated:
  "Does any C++ code rely on shared-copy semantics?"
  Examined all emCore consumers (emListBox.cpp, emFileSelectionBox.cpp)
  and all outside-emCore consumers (emStocks: 6 files). Usage pattern
  is consistent: values are stored in list items, retrieved by
  GetItemData(), and immediately extracted via emCastAnything<T>.
  No code path was found that keeps two emAnything values and relies
  on them sharing the same underlying data.
  The emStocks code uses emCastAnything<bool>(true) as a typed tag
  for marking items obsolete (emStocksControlPanel.cpp:1211).

  Verified: emTest/emTestContainers.cpp TestAnything() function
  (lines 357-369) uses store-retrieve-extract pattern only:
  - a1 = emCastAnything<int>(4711) — wrap int into a1
  - a2 = a1 — copy a1 to a2
  - a1 = emCastAnything<const char*>("Hello") — reassign a1
  - assert a2 still contains int 4711
  This pattern does NOT require shared semantics. Each variable owns
  its own data; test verifies that reassigning a1 doesn't affect a2,
  which works identically with move-only Box<dyn Any>.

Conclusion: Box<dyn Any> is sufficient. No port needed. All usage
patterns are store-retrieve-extract with no sharing dependence.
